        "The original random walk has changing level and slowly decaying ACF. Its first difference is approximately white noise. This is exactly the logic that leads to differencing in ARIMA modeling.\n",
        "\n",
        "## 3.17 Common mistakes\n",
        "\n",
        "### Mistake 1: Treating any slowly decaying ACF as AR(1)\n",
        "\n",
        "A slowly decaying ACF may come from a stationary AR(1) with $\\phi$ close to $1$, but it may also come from a trend or random walk. Always inspect the time plot.\n",
        "\n",
        "### Mistake 2: Confusing white noise with normality\n",
        "\n",
        "White noise is about mean, variance, and autocorrelation. Gaussianity is a separate distributional assumption.\n",
        "\n",
        "### Mistake 3: Assuming stationarity because a plot looks noisy\n",
        "\n",
        "A series can look noisy and still have changing variance or seasonal dependence.\n",
        "\n",
        "### Mistake 4: Overusing formal tests\n",
        "\n",
        "Formal stationarity tests are useful, but they do not replace modeling judgment. In large samples, tiny deviations become significant. In small samples, important deviations may be missed.\n",
        "\n",
        "### Mistake 5: Forgetting that sample ACF is random\n",
        "\n",
        "A sample ACF is an estimate. It fluctuates from sample to sample. Do not overinterpret one isolated spike.\n",
        "\n",
        "## 3.18 AI-assisted study and modeling\n",
        "\n",
        "AI tools can be helpful in this chapter, but only if the prompts force mathematical reasoning and verification.\n",
        "\n",
        "### Prompt 1: ask for assumptions\n",
        "\n",
        "> I have a time series with a slowly decaying sample ACF. List at least four possible explanations, including both stationary and nonstationary possibilities. For each explanation, tell me what additional diagnostic plot or transformation I should check.\n",
        "\n",
        "A good answer should mention near-unit-root AR behavior, random walk, deterministic trend, seasonality, and structural breaks.\n",
        "\n",
        "### Prompt 2: ask for a derivation\n",
        "\n",
        "> Derive the autocovariance function of an AR(1) process $X_t=\\phi X_{t-1}+W_t$ under $|\\phi|<1$. Show where stationarity is used.\n",
        "\n",
        "A good answer should derive\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\\gamma(0)=\\frac{\\sigma^2}{1-\\phi^2}\n",
